# Filter to USA and required years, select only needed columns
pop_usa = (
    pop_df[
        (pop_df['Entity'] == 'United States') &
        (pop_df['Year'].between(1980, 2016))
    ][['Year', 'Population, total']]
    .rename(columns={
        'Year': 'year',
        'Population, total': 'population'
    })
    .sort_values('year')
    .reset_index(drop=True)
)

# -------------------------------
# K-Means Clustering & Hexbin Plot: Victim vs Perpetrator Age
# -------------------------------

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

# Step 1: Filter out unknown Victim Ages (998) and missing Perpetrator Ages
df_valid_age = df[(df['Victim Age'] != 998) & (df['Perpetrator Age'].notna())]

# Step 2: Convert columns to numeric (coerce any invalid entries to NaN)
df_valid_age['Victim Age'] = pd.to_numeric(df_valid_age['Victim Age'], errors='coerce')
df_valid_age['Perpetrator Age'] = pd.to_numeric(df_valid_age['Perpetrator Age'], errors='coerce')

# Step 3: Drop rows with NaN or unrealistic ages (0100)
df_valid_age = df_valid_age.dropna(subset=['Victim Age', 'Perpetrator Age'])
df_valid_age = df_valid_age[
    (df_valid_age['Victim Age'] > 0) & (df_valid_age['Victim Age'] <= 100) &
    (df_valid_age['Perpetrator Age'] > 0) & (df_valid_age['Perpetrator Age'] <= 100)
]

# Step 4: Select numeric columns for clustering
X = df_valid_age[['Victim Age', 'Perpetrator Age']]

# Step 5: Scale the data
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Step 6: Fit K-Means (3 clusters)
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=42)
kmeans.fit(X_scaled)

# Step 7: Add cluster labels to the dataframe
df_valid_age['Cluster'] = kmeans.labels_

# Step 8: Compute cluster centers in original age scale
centers = scaler.inverse_transform(kmeans.cluster_centers_)

# Step 9: Hexbin plot to handle very large dataset
plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
hb = plt.hexbin(
    df_valid_age['Perpetrator Age'],
    df_valid_age['Victim Age'],
    gridsize=100,
    cmap='Blues',
    mincnt=1,
    linewidths=0.5
)
plt.colorbar(hb, label='Number of Incidents')

# Overlay cluster centers correctly
plt.scatter(
    centers[:, 1],  # Perpetrator Age
    centers[:, 0],  # Victim Age
    color='red',
    marker='X',
    s=200,
    label='Cluster Centers'
)

plt.xlabel('Perpetrator Age')
plt.ylabel('Victim Age')
plt.title('Victim vs Perpetrator Age with K-Means Clusters')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Step 10: Print cluster centers
print("Cluster centers (Victim Age, Perpetrator Age):\n", centers)

# Choropleth Map: Incident Counts by State

# Choropleth Map: Incident Counts by State (Full Names  Abbreviations)
# -------------------------------

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

# Step 1: State name  abbreviation mapping
state_abbrev = {
    'Alabama': 'AL', 'Alaska': 'AK', 'Arizona': 'AZ', 'Arkansas': 'AR',
    'California': 'CA', 'Colorado': 'CO', 'Connecticut': 'CT', 'Delaware': 'DE',
    'Florida': 'FL', 'Georgia': 'GA', 'Hawaii': 'HI', 'Idaho': 'ID',
    'Illinois': 'IL', 'Indiana': 'IN', 'Iowa': 'IA', 'Kansas': 'KS',
    'Kentucky': 'KY', 'Louisiana': 'LA', 'Maine': 'ME', 'Maryland': 'MD',
    'Massachusetts': 'MA', 'Michigan': 'MI', 'Minnesota': 'MN', 'Mississippi': 'MS',
    'Missouri': 'MO', 'Montana': 'MT', 'Nebraska': 'NE', 'Nevada': 'NV',
    'New Hampshire': 'NH', 'New Jersey': 'NJ', 'New Mexico': 'NM', 'New York': 'NY',
    'North Carolina': 'NC', 'North Dakota': 'ND', 'Ohio': 'OH', 'Oklahoma': 'OK',
    'Oregon': 'OR', 'Pennsylvania': 'PA', 'Rhode Island': 'RI',
    'South Carolina': 'SC', 'South Dakota': 'SD', 'Tennessee': 'TN',
    'Texas': 'TX', 'Utah': 'UT', 'Vermont': 'VT', 'Virginia': 'VA',
    'Washington': 'WA', 'West Virginia': 'WV', 'Wisconsin': 'WI', 'Wyoming': 'WY'
}

# Step 2: Aggregate incident counts by State
state_counts = (
    df
    .groupby('State')
    .size()
    .reset_index(name='Incident_Count')
)

# Step 3: Convert full state names to abbreviations
state_counts['State_abbrev'] = state_counts['State'].map(state_abbrev)

# Step 4: Drop rows that didn't map (e.g. UNKNOWN)
state_counts = state_counts.dropna(subset=['State_abbrev'])

# Step 5: Create choropleth
fig = px.choropleth(
    state_counts,
    locations='State_abbrev',
    locationmode='USA-states',
    color='Incident_Count',
    color_continuous_scale='Reds',
    scope='usa',
    labels={'Incident_Count': 'Number of Incidents'},
    title='Incident Counts by State (Raw Counts)'
)

# Step 6: Make map readable
fig.update_layout(
    width=1000,
    height=600
)

fig.show()

California, Texas, Florida and New York have the highest murder rates. They have larger populations and urban centres.After the top few, most states drop off sharply. The northwest is less populated and shows lower counts due to lowerpopulation density, not necessarily lower risk.

features = [
    'State',
    'Victim Sex',
    'Victim Age',
    'Victim Race',
    'Perpetrator Sex',
    'Perpetrator Age',
    'Perpetrator Race',
    'Relationship_Grouped',
    'Weapon'
]

X = df[features]
y = df['Crime Solved']

X_encoded = pd.get_dummies(X, drop_first=True)

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split( X_encoded, y, test_size=0.3, stratify=y, random_state=42 )

model = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000) model.fit(X_train, y_train)
